Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("ProductDetailsPage", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate from ProductListPage (both approaches):**
```csharp
// Simple string parameter
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"ProductDetailsPage?productId={product.Id}");

// Complex object via dictionary
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("ProductDetailsPage", new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }
});
```

**3. Receive data in your ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // String parameter approach — value arrives as a string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            LoadProduct(productId);
        }

        // Complex object approach — value arrives as the original type
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
        }
    }

    private async void LoadProduct(string id) { /* fetch from service */ }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| Syntax | interpolated URI | `Dictionary<string, object>` |
| Arrives as | `string` | original CLR type |
| Survives deep link | ✅ | ❌ |

Use string params for bookmarkable/deep-linkable routes; use object params when you already have the data in memory and want to avoid a re-fetch.
